 ('64', '11', '3', '57', 'en_ca', '2', 'EtO content added', '{\"typeId\":\"3\",\"authorId\":\"1\",\"title\":\"Sterilization Methods\",\"slug\":\"sterilization-methods\",\"postDate\":1443886560,\"expiryDate\":null,\"enabled\":1,\"fields\":{\"5\":\"\",\"7\":{\"new1\":{\"type\":\"tabList\",\"enabled\":\"1\",\"fields\":{\"tabListTitle\":\"\",\"tabs\":{\"new1\":{\"type\":\"1\",\"fields\":{\"tabTitle\":\"Ethylene Oxide\",\"tabIcon\":\"oxide\",\"tabContent\":\"Ethylene oxide (EtO) sterilization uses EtO gas to sterilize equipment that requires lower temperatures. It is widely used across the sterilization industry for its proven methods as well as its universal compatibility: most products can be sterilized using ethylene oxide gas, including devices that contain plastic or electronic components. EtO infiltrates packaging, allowing it to sterilize organisms on a product from manufacturing and packaging processes. As sterilizers have been using EtO sterilization since the 1950s, there is a lot of information on this method. It is reliable, requires low capital investment, and most sterilizers know exactly what they are getting into when they use it. However, there are also disadvantages to using EtO gas. It is a fairly complex process, and requires longer product holdup for airing. Because of its complexity, as well as its explosive quality, a proven and detailed control system is essential.  There are three phases to sterilizing with ethylene oxide. First is pre-conditioning, where a batch is prepared for sterilizers using humidity so organisms grow. Once this is done, the batch is moved to the sterilization phase. The sterilization phase is long and complex; and must be closely monitored for accuracy and safety. Our software creates ease-of-access and use for process monitoring while creating detailed reports for documentation and auto-batch release. After sterilization is complete, a batch must be degassed in a temperature-controlled environment. This removes any EtO from the product, insuring safety, before batches are shipped for use.\"}}}}}},\"4\":\"\"}}', '2015-12-29 19:02:15', '2015-12-29 19:02:15', 'f5ecb1d8-6494-423d-840e-db1318890e24'),
 ('65', '11', '3', '57', 'en_ca', '3', 'adding in additional format option for text (with sample content) for comparison purposes', '{\"typeId\":\"3\",\"authorId\":\"1\",\"title\":\"Sterilization Methods\",\"slug\":\"sterilization-methods\",\"postDate\":1443886560,\"expiryDate\":null,\"enabled\":1,\"fields\":{\"5\":\"\",\"7\":{\"58\":{\"type\":\"tabList\",\"enabled\":\"1\",\"fields\":{\"tabListTitle\":\"We could title this list ... \",\"tabs\":{\"59\":{\"type\":\"1\",\"fields\":{\"tabTitle\":\"Ethylene Oxide\",\"tabIcon\":\"oxide\",\"tabContent\":\"Ethylene oxide (EtO) sterilization uses EtO gas to sterilize equipment that requires lower temperatures. It is widely used across the sterilization industry for its proven methods as well as its universal compatibility: most products can be sterilized using ethylene oxide gas, including devices that contain plastic or electronic components. EtO infiltrates packaging, allowing it to sterilize organisms on a product from manufacturing and packaging processes. As sterilizers have been using EtO sterilization since the 1950s, there is a lot of information on this method. It is reliable, requires low capital investment, and most sterilizers know exactly what they are getting into when they use it. However, there are also disadvantages to using EtO gas. It is a fairly complex process, and requires longer product holdup for airing. Because of its complexity, as well as its explosive quality, a proven and detailed control system is essential.  There are three phases to sterilizing with ethylene oxide. First is pre-conditioning, where a batch is prepared for sterilizers using humidity so organisms grow. Once this is done, the batch is moved to the sterilization phase. The sterilization phase is long and complex; and must be closely monitored for accuracy and safety. Our software creates ease-of-access and use for process monitoring while creating detailed reports for documentation and auto-batch release. After sterilization is complete, a batch must be degassed in a temperature-controlled environment. This removes any EtO from the product, insuring safety, before batches are shipped for use.\"}},\"new1\":{\"type\":\"1\",\"fields\":{\"tabTitle\":\"Gamma\",\"tabIcon\":\"gamma\",\"tabContent\":\"This content needs to be added\"}},\"new2\":{\"type\":\"1\",\"fields\":{\"tabTitle\":\"E-Beam\",\"tabIcon\":\"ebeam\",\"tabContent\":\"This content needs to be added\"}},\"new3\":{\"type\":\"1\",\"fields\":{\"tabTitle\":\"X-Ray\",\"tabIcon\":\"xray\",\"tabContent\":\"This content needs to be added\"}}}}},\"new1\":{\"type\":\"featureList\",\"enabled\":\"1\",\"fields\":{\"mainHeading\":\"Here are some methods of sterilization\",\"mainContent\":\"Is there a quick sentence that could introduce the text below?\",\"features\":{\"new1\":{\"type\":\"2\",\"fields\":{\"featureHeading\":\"EtO\",\"featureContent\":\"<p>Ethylene oxide (EtO) sterilization uses EtO gas to sterilize equipment that requires lower temperatures. It is widely used across the sterilization industry for its proven methods as well as its universal compatibility: most products can be sterilized using ethylene oxide gas, including devices that contain plastic or electronic components. EtO infiltrates packaging, allowing it to sterilize organisms on a product from manufacturing and packaging processes.\\r\\n<\\/p><p>As sterilizers have been using EtO sterilization since the 1950s, there is a lot of information on this method. It is reliable, requires low capital investment, and most sterilizers know exactly what they are getting into when they use it. However, there are also disadvantages to using EtO gas. It is a fairly complex process, and requires longer product holdup for airing. Because of its complexity, as well as its explosive quality, a proven and detailed control system is essential.\\r\\n<\\/p><p>There are three phases to sterilizing with ethylene oxide. First is pre-conditioning, where a batch is prepared for sterilizers using humidity so organisms grow. Once this is done, the batch is moved to the sterilization phase. The sterilization phase is long and complex; and must be closely monitored for accuracy and safety. Our software creates ease-of-access and use for process monitoring while creating detailed reports for documentation and auto-batch release.\\r\\n<\\/p><p>After sterilization is complete, a batch must be degassed in a temperature-controlled environment. This removes any EtO from the product, insuring safety, before batches are shipped for use.\\r\\n<\\/p>\"}},\"new2\":{\"type\":\"2\",\"fields\":{\"featureHeading\":\"Gamma\",\"featureContent\":\"<p>This content is missing<\\/p>\"}},\"new3\":{\"type\":\"2\",\"fields\":{\"featureHeading\":\"E-Beam\",\"featureContent\":\"<p>This content is missing<\\/p>\"}},\"new4\":{\"type\":\"2\",\"fields\":{\"featureHeading\":\"X-Ray\",\"featureContent\":\"<p>This content is missing<\\/p>\"}}}}}},\"4\":\"\"}}', '2015-12-29 19:08:45', '2015-12-29 19:08:45', '8bc6e87b-9d5d-4d67-a88c-279a9f2795b4'),
 ('66', '2', '1', '57', 'en_ca', '12', 'Adding in (not final) to the modalities content', '{\"typeId\":\"1\",\"authorId\":null,\"title\":\"Konnexis\",\"slug\":\"homepage\",\"postDate\":1445093378,\"expiryDate\":null,\"enabled\":1,\"fields\":{\"5\":[\"4\"],\"7\":{\"28\":{\"type\":\"textWithPhoto\",\"enabled\":\"1\",\"fields\":{\"backgroundColor\":\"white\",\"sectionHeading\":\"Global Market Leaders\",\"textContent\":\"<p>Peter Veselovsky recognized the need for an expert in sterilization software, and Konnexis Inc. was created to meet this need. As a global market leader in sterilization control systems, Konnexis Inc. remains dedicated to the sterilization industry, providing future-proof control systems for sterilizers across the globe.\\r\\n<\\/p>\",\"callToActionText\":\"About\",\"callToActionLink\":[\"13\"],\"photo\":[\"33\"],\"photoAlignment\":\"right\"}},\"29\":{\"type\":\"previewTiles\",\"enabled\":\"1\",\"fields\":{\"pages\":[\"5\",\"6\"],\"tileType\":\"overlay\"}},\"35\":{\"type\":\"tabList\",\"enabled\":\"1\",\"fields\":{\"tabListTitle\":\"Sterilization Methods\",\"tabs\":{\"new1\":{\"type\":\"1\",\"fields\":{\"tabTitle\":\"Ethylene Oxide (Eto)\",\"tabIcon\":\"oxide\",\"tabContent\":\"(Not final) tbc\"}},\"37\":{\"type\":\"1\",\"fields\":{\"tabTitle\":\"Gamma Irradiation\",\"tabIcon\":\"gamma\",\"tabContent\":\"(Not final) Konnexis has developed a system for Gamma and E-Beam irradiators that is highly flexible in order to both suit your needs and to accommodate for the changing industry. Through seamless integration between irradiator control and product tracking, Konnexis has allowed its Gamma irradiation customers to reach unparalleled levels of productivity.\"}},\"38\":{\"type\":\"1\",\"fields\":{\"tabTitle\":\"Electron Beam (E-Beam)\",\"tabIcon\":\"ebeam\",\"tabContent\":\"(Not final) Konnexis has developed a system for Gamma and E-Beam irradiators that is highly flexible in order to both suit your needs and to accommodate for the changing industry. Through seamless integration between irradiator control and product tracking, Konnexis has allowed its Gamma irradiation customers to reach unparalleled levels of productivity.\"}},\"39\":{\"type\":\"1\",\"fields\":{\"tabTitle\":\"X-Ray\",\"tabIcon\":\"xray\",\"tabContent\":\"(Not final) Konnexis\' innovation in X-Ray sterilization has accelerated the industry and allowed the technology to advance to new heights. Through seamless integration between irradiator control and product tracking, Konnexis allows you effortless processing and reliability.\"}}}}},\"30\":{\"type\":\"oneColumnText\",\"enabled\":\"1\",\"fields\":{\"heading\":\"Products & Services\",\"columnText\":\"<p>We have a range of proven solutions that have undergone rigorous testing to provide you with a reliable and dependable solution for any sterilization modality. Our control systems are being used throughout the world which sterilize over 1 million pallets per year.\\r\\n<\\/p>\",\"backgroundColor\":\"grey\",\"centerText\":\"1\"}},\"31\":{\"type\":\"previewTiles\",\"enabled\":\"1\",\"fields\":{\"pages\":[\"8\",\"9\",\"10\"],\"tileType\":\"titleBar\"}},\"32\":{\"type\":\"testimonialSlider\",\"enabled\":\"1\",\"fields\":{\"testimonials\":[\"14\"]}},\"34\":{\"type\":\"callToAction\",\"enabled\":\"1\",\"fields\":{\"introHeading\":\"For more information or to request a quote\",\"ctaButtonText\":\"Contact Us\",\"ctaButtonLink\":[\"13\"],\"backgroundColor\":\"grey\"}}},\"3\":\"Global Market Leaders in Sterilization Control and Monitoring Systems\",\"4\":\"Advanced monitoring solutions designed for the sterilization industry, for growth, production efficiency and the long term.\"}}', '2015-12-30 17:03:14', '2015-12-30 17:03:14', '616b37cb-c686-48e7-8ade-3987ca7edfeb'),
 ('67', '11', '3', '57', 'en_ca', '4', 'Adding in the modalities content', '{\"typeId\":\"3\",\"authorId\":\"\",\"title\":\"Sterilization Methods\",\"slug\":\"sterilization-methods\",\"postDate\":1443886560,\"expiryDate\":null,\"enabled\":1,\"fields\":{\"5\":\"\",\"7\":{\"new3\":{\"type\":\"tabList\",\"enabled\":\"1\",\"fields\":{\"tabListTitle\":\"Click on each to learn more\",\"tabs\":{\"new1\":{\"type\":\"1\",\"fields\":{\"tabTitle\":\"Ethylene Oxide\",\"tabIcon\":\"oxide\",\"tabContent\":\"(Gregor: add jump link)\"}},\"new2\":{\"type\":\"1\",\"fields\":{\"tabTitle\":\"Gamma Irradiation\",\"tabIcon\":\"gamma\",\"tabContent\":\"(Gregor: add jump link)\"}},\"new4\":{\"type\":\"1\",\"fields\":{\"tabTitle\":\"E-Beam\",\"tabIcon\":\"ebeam\",\"tabContent\":\"(Gregor: add jump link)\"}},\"new3\":{\"type\":\"1\",\"fields\":{\"tabTitle\":\"X-Ray\",\"tabIcon\":\"xray\",\"tabContent\":\"(Gregor: add jump link)\"}}}}},\"new1\":{\"type\":\"oneColumnText\",\"enabled\":\"1\",\"fields\":{\"heading\":\"\\u200bEthylene oxide (EtO)\",\"columnText\":\"<p>Ethylene oxide (EtO) sterilization uses EtO gas to sterilize equipment that requires lower temperatures. It is widely used across the sterilization industry for its proven methods as well as its universal compatibility: most products can be sterilized using ethylene oxide gas, including devices that contain plastic or electronic components. EtO infiltrates packaging, allowing it to sterilize organisms on a product from manufacturing and packaging processes.\\r\\n<\\/p><p>As sterilizers have been using EtO sterilization since the 1950s, there is a lot of information on this method. It is reliable, requires low capital investment, and most sterilizers know exactly what they are getting into when they use it. However, there are also disadvantages to using EtO gas. It is a fairly complex process, and requires longer product holdup for airing. Because of its complexity, as well as its explosive quality, a proven and detailed control system is essential.\\r\\n<\\/p><p>There are three phases to sterilizing with ethylene oxide. First is pre-conditioning, where a batch is prepared for sterilizers using humidity so organisms grow. Once this is done, the batch is moved to the sterilization phase. The sterilization phase is long and complex; and must be closely monitored for accuracy and safety. Our software creates ease-of-access and use for process monitoring while creating detailed reports for documentation and auto-batch release.\\r\\n<\\/p><p>After sterilization is complete, a batch must be degassed in a temperature-controlled environment. This removes any EtO from the product, insuring safety, before batches are shipped for use.\\r\\n<\\/p>\",\"backgroundColor\":\"white\",\"centerText\":\"\"}},\"new4\":{\"type\":\"oneColumnText\",\"enabled\":\"1\",\"fields\":{\"heading\":\"Gamma Irradiation Sterilization\",\"columnText\":\"<p>Gamma rays are like x-rays as they are a form of electromagnetic radiation, only a gamma ray is much stronger than an x-ray. Gamma rays easily pass through plastic to kill bacteria and come from radionuclide elements, or an isotope source. During radioactive decay, one of these elements (such as the Cobalt 60) will cause ionization, emitting gamma rays.\\r\\n<\\/p><p>Like with ethylene oxide sterilization, sterilization using gamma irradiation is a proven method. It has been used for many years, and is safe to use under specific parameters. Gamma dosage is measured using dosimeters for parametric release. Our control systems help you meet those parameters to ensure a safer quality of sterilization.\\r\\n<\\/p><p>Gamma irradiation does not generate heat or moisture, so it can be used for various products. One benefit over the use of ethylene oxide for sterilization is that gamma irradiation does not leave residual radioactivity, and a degassing phase is not required.\\r\\n<\\/p>\",\"backgroundColor\":\"white\",\"centerText\":\"\"}},\"new5\":{\"type\":\"oneColumnText\",\"enabled\":\"1\",\"fields\":{\"heading\":\"Electron-Beam (E-Beam) Radiation Sterilization\",\"columnText\":\"<p>Like with gamma irradiation, electron-beam radiation ionizes energy for sterilization. It is a proven method that has been around since the 1950s. Though the electron beam was highly unreliable when the technology was first released, advances have improved the operation of e-beam radiation technology and its efficiency.\\r\\n<\\/p><p>E-beam radiation and gamma irradiation are similar methods used for sterilization, but there are some differences. E-beam rays cannot penetrate a product as deeply as gamma rays. While gamma rays may increase the energy of electrons after released, e-beam electrons\\u2019 energy decreases. The e-beam method kills organisms more directly than gamma. Their high-energy output as soon as they are released increase the dosage of the e-beam as the medical device is penetrated. As a result, e-beam has a high dose rate with a lower level of penetration, the opposite of gamma irradiation.\\r\\n<\\/p><p>E-beam is best used for higher-volume products of low value, but can also be used for low-volume products of high value. It performs best with products of low density. Due to the difference in dosage rates between gamma irradiation and e-beam radiation, some products show less decay when sterilized using e-beam technology.\\r\\n<\\/p><p>Due to its sensitive nature, e-beam requires stringent control. A beam\\u2019s current, scan width, energy, and the rate at which product is carried through a sterilizer can effect e-beam\\u2019s ability to sterilize equipment<a href=\\\"https:\\/\\/konnexisinc.sharepoint.com\\/Customers\\/Electron-Beam%20Radiation_Comments.docx#_msocom_5\\\"> <\\/a>properly. A process-monitoringcontrol system is essential to ensure efficiency and consistency in e-beam sterilization.\\r\\n<\\/p>\",\"backgroundColor\":\"white\",\"centerText\":\"\"}},\"new6\":{\"type\":\"oneColumnText\",\"enabled\":\"1\",\"fields\":{\"heading\":\"X-Ray\",\"columnText\":\"<p>To be added\\r\\n<\\/p>\",\"backgroundColor\":\"white\",\"centerText\":\"\"}}},\"4\":\"\"}}', '2015-12-30 17:23:38', '2015-12-30 17:23:38', '867defd0-a3c2-4276-be19-c7acd5f6b4be');




